$$\\textit{As traduções virão mais tarde..} \\\\$$

You can multiply fractions so that you multiply the numerators
and the denominators (and then simplify if possible).
$$\\\\[4ex] \\text{Example:}\\quad
\\frac{a}{b} \\cdot \\frac{c}{d}
= \\frac{a\\cdot c}{b\\cdot d}
= \\frac{ac}{bd}
\\\\[4ex]
\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{a}{2} \\cdot \\frac{b}{c}
= \\frac{a\\cdot b}{2\\cdot c}
= \\frac{ab}{2c} \\\\[4ex]$$

You can divide fractions so that you multiply the numerator by the
reciprocal of the denominator.
$$\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{\\frac{a}{b}}{\\frac{c}{d}}
= \\frac{a}{b} \\cdot \\frac{d}{c}
= \\frac{ad}{bc}
\\\\[4ex]
\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{\\frac{a}{3}}{2}
= \\frac{a}{3} : 2
= \\frac{a}{3} \\cdot \\frac{1}{2}
= \\frac{a}{6} \\\\[4ex]$$

If there is a shared factor in the numerator and the denominator,
it can be cancelled.

 $$\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{10}{15}
= \\frac{2 \\cdot \\rlap{\,/}{5}}{3 \\cdot \\rlap{\,/}{5}}
= \\frac{2}{3}
\\\\[4ex]

\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{a \\rlap{\,/}{x}y}{bz \\rlap{\,/}{x}}
= \\frac{ay}{bz}
\\\\[4ex]

\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{w(a-2)}{a-2}
= \\frac{w \\cdot (a-2)}{1 \\cdot (a-2)}
= w
\\\\[4ex]$$

You may have to factor to be able to reduce the fraction.

 $$\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{ab+ac}{b+c}
= \\frac{a \\cdot (b+c)}{(b+c)}
= a
\\\\[4ex]$$

You can factor a fraction by any number or expression,
zero excluded. Factoring means that both the numerator and
the denominator are multiplied by the same expression.

$$\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{a}{b}
= \\frac{2a}{2b}
\\\\[4ex]$$

If fractions have the same denominator, you can add or subtract
them so that you add or subtract only the numerators,
and keep that same denominator.

$$\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{5}{2} + \\frac{4}{2}
= \\frac{5+4}{2}
= \\frac{9}{2}
\\\\[4ex]

\\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{2}{s} + \\frac{x}{s}
= \\frac{2+x}{s}
\\\\[4ex]

 \\text{Example:} \\quad
\\frac{2x}{x+1} - \\frac{5}{x+1}
= \\frac{2x-5}{x+1}
\\\\[4ex]
$$

If necessary, you must factor the fractions before adding or subtracting
so that they have the same denominator.

$$\\text{Example:} \\quad$$
$$^{2)}\\frac{1}{7} + ^{7)}\\frac{3}{2}$$
$$= \\frac{2 \\cdot 1}{2 \\cdot 7} + \\frac{7 \\cdot 3}{7 \\cdot 2}$$
$$= \\frac{2+21}{14}$$
$$= \\frac {23}{14}$$
$$\\\\[4ex]$$

$$\\text{Example:} \\quad$$
$$\\frac{1}{6x} + ^{2)}\\frac{5}{3x} + ^{3)}\\frac{3}{2x}$$
$$ = \\frac{1}{6x} + \\frac{10}{6x} + \\frac{9}{6x}$$
$$ = \\frac{1+10+9}{6x}$$
$$= \\frac {20}{6x}$$
$$= \\frac {10}{3x}$$
$$\\\\[4ex]$$

$$\\text{Example:} \\quad$$
$$^{a)}\\frac{5}{b} - ^{b)}\\frac{4}{a}$$
$$= \\frac{5a}{ab} - \\frac{4b}{ab}$$
$$= \\frac{5a-4b}{ab}$$
